EXECUTIVE SUMMARY

This document evaluates the operational viability of the definition of Artificial General Intelligence (AGI) as articulated by Sam Altman, herein referred to as the Infinite Perfect Memory Criterion (IPMC).

Sam Altman has publicly asserted that:

“Humans do not have infinite perfect memory, and AI definitely will.”

Under this formulation, infinite perfect memory is not presented metaphorically, aspirationally, or heuristically. It is framed as:
	•	the decisive differentiator between biological cognition and artificial cognition
	•	the breakthrough condition for AGI
	•	the foundational capability enabling “real” intelligence

This paper performs a structured feasibility audit of the IPMC within the constraints of:
	1.	Information theory
	2.	Thermodynamics
	3.	Relativity
	4.	Cosmology
	5.	Quantum mechanics
	6.	Computational complexity

Our findings are unambiguous:

The Infinite Perfect Memory Criterion is physically non-implementable in a finite universe.

Therefore:

If AGI is defined as requiring infinite perfect memory, AGI — under Sam Altman’s definition — is physically impossible.

If AGI does not require infinite perfect memory, then the defining claim collapses.

Both propositions cannot simultaneously be true.

